# Recommended model — event-driven SDLC control plane and loop architecture critique

External adversarial analysis of the Verdify wave/loop/lane design (walk transcript
SRC: loop-topology). Reconciles James's topology layer with Jason's operating
contract. Reported analysis; several capability claims and citations are post-cutoff
and MUST be independently verified before being treated as load-bearing.

## Core reconciliation

James describes the TOPOLOGY (planning loop, implementation loop, controller, lanes).
Jason describes the OPERATING CONTRACT (North Star, traceability, approvals,
acceptance criteria, CI/CD gates, human feedback). Reconciliation:

> A wave is NOT itself a loop. A wave is a versioned delivery envelope that moves
> through a durable state machine. Inside that wave, task-level implementation and
> repair loops execute concurrently.

The architecture should be a vendor-neutral, event-driven SDLC control plane. Claude
Code and Codex are replaceable execution engines, not the durable controller or
source of truth.

## Most important critiques (current thinking -> recommended change)

- Controller as "god of the repo" -> too much authority/hidden state in one model
  context. Make the controller a DETERMINISTIC STATE MACHINE backed by a durable
  event log. Models propose plans/actions; the control plane authorizes transitions.
- North Star traces to every future button/API/issue -> exhaustive future
  decomposition goes stale. Use ROLLING-WAVE PLANNING: complete outcome-level
  traceability for the roadmap, but decompose only the next one or two waves to
  issue-level contracts.
- Milestone maps 1:1 to a worktree -> different kinds of objects. A milestone is a
  product outcome; a worktree is temporary execution isolation. Use one worktree per
  active write task or conflict domain, not per milestone.
- Lanes are frontend/API/database/backend -> useful seed, too static. Derive lanes
  per wave from the dependency graph and file-conflict graph. A lane is a temporary
  scheduling partition, not a permanent codebase silo.
- Lane agent decides its sprint -> lets execution agents redefine committed scope.
  The wave planner owns committed scope and issue sequencing; a lane agent may make a
  local implementation plan, but scope changes are explicit change requests.
- Controller polls terminals every five minutes -> brittle as primary protocol.
  Consume structured worker events and webhooks; use heartbeats and lease expiry only
  to detect lost workers, not to scrape terminal output.
- First coding pass may run without adversarial audit -> too weak. Every candidate
  gets deterministic checks plus fresh-context review before integration; the
  cumulative wave diff also needs review.
- CI green means the wave is ready -> necessary, not sufficient. Also require story
  acceptance evidence, security policy, migration validation, observability checks,
  and cumulative integration review.
- "Claude has subagents; Codex has nothing" -> no longer current (as of mid-2026).
  Codex now supports explicit parallel subagent workflows (recommended for bounded
  exploration/testing/triage/read-heavy work; parallel writers increase conflict
  cost). Claude still has richer in-session team semantics (shared tasks, teammate
  messaging, idle notifications) but agent teams remain experimental with resumption/
  stale-state/shutdown limits -> Claude internal team state must NOT become Orbit's
  durable program state.

## Definitions that resolve the debate

- North Star: versioned product outcomes, user groups, architectural principles,
  NFRs, constraints, non-goals, product-level success measures.
- Milestone: an observable capability/outcome that can be demonstrated and accepted.
  Never a branch or worktree.
- Wave: an approved, bounded delivery envelope of user stories, tasks, dependencies,
  risk limits, and exit evidence. The unit presented for human/Orbit review.
- User story: integrated user-observable behavior with acceptance scenarios.
  Generally vertical even when implementation crosses lanes.
- Task / issue: the smallest independently implementable, reviewable, mergeable work
  contract. Need not equal exactly one method or file.
- Lane: a temporary execution partition of tasks one worker can own without colliding
  with other active writers.
- Attempt: one worker run against a task contract. A failed attempt does not alter
  the task's committed objective.
- Evidence: test outputs, build results, screenshots, security findings, review
  results, deployment identifiers, and other artifacts proving acceptance.

Remove "sprint" from the agent vocabulary. Wave = human/Orbit review cadence; Task =
committed implementation unit; Attempt plan = lane worker's private step sequence.

## Decision rights (answers "who decides?")

- Product priority / North Star change: human or delegated Orbit policy.
- Proposed wave objective and stories: wave-planning agent.
- Approval of wave scope: human initially; risk policy may later auto-approve
  low-risk waves.
- Task decomposition and dependency DAG: planning agent + deterministic schema and
  dependency validation.
- Assignment to lanes: scheduler, based on readiness, path conflicts, risk, worker
  availability.
- Local implementation steps: lane worker.
- Expansion/alteration of task scope: controller via a versioned change request;
  never silently by the worker.
- Whether a task is a CANDIDATE for completion: worker may report candidate_done.
- Whether a task is ACTUALLY complete: deterministic checks + independent verifier.
- Whether a wave is technically releasable: integration CI, security, acceptance.
- Whether a wave meets product intent: human or authorized Orbit reviewer.
- Production deployment: risk policy; high-risk requires explicit human approval.

## Control-plane boundaries

- Git is the durable source of truth for approved plans, code, ADRs, instructions,
  skills, acceptance specs.
- GitHub is the human collaboration surface for issues, PRs, comments, reviews,
  approvals.
- The runtime state store is the EXECUTION source of truth for claims, leases,
  attempt numbers, events, costs, heartbeats, blockers, normalized provider state.
- CI and policy are the gate authority.
- The model is a worker/proposer; it does not directly mutate authoritative state
  from running to done. A model emits events: candidate_done, blocked,
  scope_change_requested, human_decision_required, retry_recommended. The controller
  validates the event, checks policy, and commits the transition.

## Normalized worker adapter

Both vendors implement one interface: start(task, workspace, policy)->RunId;
events(runId)->AsyncIterable<RunEvent>; send(runId, message); cancel(runId, reason);
collect(runId)->ResultPacket.

Normalized RunEvent kinds: run.started, task.oriented, plan.created,
command.started, file.changed, test.completed, progress.reported, decision.requested,
task.blocked, candidate.completed, run.failed, run.stopped.

Codex noninteractive mode emits a JSONL stream (lifecycle/command/file-change/plan/
completion) and the Codex SDK can create/resume threads. Claude Agent SDK provides
programmatic access to the same loop/tool capabilities. These beat SSHing into tmux
and reading terminal text.

## Outer repo/wave loop (state machine)

States/transitions: Observe -> DraftWave (snapshot North Star, backlog, repo, CI,
telemetry, feedback) -> Approve (changes requested loops to DraftWave; human/policy
approval -> Execute) -> Verify (bounded repair -> Execute; dependency/scope
invalidated -> Replan; task evidence passes -> Integrate) -> Integrate (merge/
integration failure -> Execute; all wave gates pass -> DeployPreview) -> Review
(stories accepted -> Accept; defects/new feedback -> Replan) -> Accept -> Observe;
Replan -> DraftWave. Escalate transitions out of Execute/Verify on risk, retry, cost,
or stagnation limits -> human/Orbit decision -> DraftWave. Planning and implementation
are PHASES of one wave lifecycle, not two separate loops; replan is an explicit
transition.

## Correct planning-pass order

1. Snapshot facts (merged code, open PRs, CI, telemetry, feedback, backlog,
   unresolved decisions, current North Star).
2. Select next outcome; define wave objective.
3. Define user stories + acceptance evidence.
4. Discover implementation delta.
5. Derive/update tasks and dependencies.
6. Calculate write conflicts, sequencing, risk, capacity.
7. Materialize/update GitHub issues.
8. Produce an immutable proposed WavePlan.
9. Approve it. 10. Execute it.

Issues are an OUTPUT of planning, not the raw plan. Once approved the wave is
versioned; material scope changes require a wave amendment (audit record),
decommitting a task, or ending the wave and creating a replanned successor. No agent
silently adds "while I'm here" work.

## Inner execution-controller loop (reconciler)

Approved WavePlan -> ready task? -> claim with lease -> isolated branch+worktree ->
run provider worker -> worker events: progress (persist, refresh lease); blocked
(classify: dependency-not-ready -> schedule others; task-contract-wrong -> request
replan; decision-required -> escalate); candidate_done -> independent verification
(failed+budget -> repair attempt with focused validation delta; passed -> queue merge
to wave branch -> integration CI (failed -> classify; passed+work remains -> next
ready; passed+stories complete -> wave evidence bundle)).

The controller is a RECONCILER, not a chat session that wakes and asks everyone what
happened. On every event: load durable state; validate event vs state+policy; apply
idempotent transition; schedule newly ready tasks; enforce retry/cost/risk/time
budgets; persist decision + evidence. A periodic process detects expired leases,
missing heartbeats, lost jobs, stale PRs, undelivered CI events, and GitHub/controller
state mismatches; it does not infer progress from terminal text.

## Lane/task execution loop

Orient -> LocalPlan -> ReproduceOrTest -> Implement -> LocalChecks (actionable
failure loops to Implement) -> SelfReview -> CommitCandidate -> IndependentReview
(fix requested + budget -> Implement; accepted -> CandidateDone). Escalate from
LocalChecks (no progress/retry limit) or IndependentReview (ambiguous/high risk).
Trivial changes may have a one/two-step LocalPlan. Explicit stops: validation passes,
attempt limit reached, remaining delta stops changing, or next decision needs human
review. Keep findings/changes/validation-result/remaining-delta as an audit record
per pass.

No self-certification: the implementer can only say "I believe this is a candidate;
here is the evidence." A fresh-context verifier determines whether the task contract
was satisfied (review in a fresh subagent context that sees diff+requirements, not the
implementer's reasoning). Evidence strength order: (1) deterministic tests/schemas/
static analysis/builds/policy; (2) behavior-level test or browser evidence; (3)
fresh-context review vs task contract; (4) LLM semantic judgment for not-yet-testable
requirements; (5) human review for ambiguity/high risk.

## Traceability model

North Star (outcomes, constraints, NFRs) -> Milestone (observable capability) -> Wave
(approved delivery envelope) -> User story (behavior + acceptance) -> Task/GitHub
issue (implementation contract) -> Run attempt (provider, prompt, tools, cost) ->
Commit + task PR -> Evidence (tests, review, security, screenshots) -> Preview/release
-> Feedback/telemetry -> Wave. Traceability is COMPLETE for what is currently
committed, not falsely detailed for every hypothetical feature. Each object supports
both directions ("why are we changing this file?" and "what proves this story
works?").

Product-level vs issue-level security: review the cumulative wave diff and intended
end state, not only isolated task PRs. (A mid-2026 preprint reportedly found
individually routine tickets compose into vulnerable outcomes that are less visible
when reviewed independently — early research, supports a wave-integration threat/intent
review.)

## Typed task and wave contracts

Task contract fields: task_id, wave_id, story_ids, goal, non_goals, dependencies,
write_scope (expected_paths + additional_paths_require_change_request), acceptance
(deterministic commands + behavior scenarios), required_evidence, risk (class +
reasons), budgets (max_attempts, max_no_progress_attempts), escalate_when.

Wave contract adds: wave_id, north_star_version, objective, stories (id + acceptance),
committed_tasks, exit_gates (all_committed_tasks_terminal, integration_ci_green,
cumulative_security_review_passed, acceptance_scenarios_passed,
preview_deployment_healthy, evidence_bundle_complete), approval (mode + approved_version).

## Codex vs Claude implementation

Codex: use the Codex SDK for durable threads or `codex exec --json` for a process
adapter with structured events; subagents must be requested explicitly; use for
exploration/test/log/review read tasks; separate worktrees for concurrent writers;
avoid overlapping write scopes. Codex hooks have limits (no async handlers, only
command handlers, some pre-tool stop fields unsupported) -> keep cross-vendor
invariants in the controller/sandbox/CI.

Claude: use the Claude Agent SDK for production orchestration; custom subagent for
exploration/test/verification; agent teams only when peer communication helps;
worktrees for concurrent writers; dynamic workflows for codified stage-local fan-outs
(audits/migrations). Teams work best for independent tasks, not sequential/same-file/
dependency-heavy work; begin with research/review, assign distinct file ownership,
keep teams small. Dynamic workflows do not accept ordinary mid-run user input and
resume only within the same session -> treat one workflow as a bounded execution
stage, not the outer controller.

Common policy: one active writer per worktree and branch; parallelize only tasks whose
dependencies are satisfied and whose expected write sets do not conflict.

## Platform build milestones (prove correctness before parallelism)

- M0 Contracts and state machine: versioned schemas for North Star, wave, story, task,
  attempt, event, evidence, approval, deployment. Invalid transitions rejected; every
  transition auditable + idempotent. No coding agents yet.
- M1 Single-task closed loop: one approved task -> branch/worktree -> one provider ->
  local checks -> candidate PR. Task can finish/block/fail/escalate without manual
  state repair.
- M2 Independent verification: fresh-context verifier, deterministic evidence packet,
  bounded repair attempts, stagnation detection. Worker cannot mark itself done.
- M3 Sequential wave: North Star snapshot -> approved WavePlan -> several sequential
  tasks -> wave branch -> preview deployment -> review packet.
- M4 Parallel lanes: task DAG, leases, conflict map, isolated worktrees, integration
  queue, event-driven monitoring. 2-4 independent writers without duplicate work,
  overwritten files, or uncontrolled scope drift.
- M5 Provider parity: Codex and Claude adapters produce the same normalized events and
  result packet; same benchmark task set runs through either provider.
- M6 Risk-based autonomy: policy classes, sandbox profiles, permission scopes, approval
  gates, separate deployment identities. Low-risk auto-integrates; high-risk pauses.
- M7 Learning and eval loop: run traces, human feedback, regression cases, skill
  versions, controlled harness-change PRs. A repeated failure becomes a reproducible
  eval before instructions/skills change.
- M8 Orbit multi-repo loop: cross-repo priorities, dependency graph, release
  coordination, shared policy, portfolio feedback. Parallelism does not make an
  unreliable single-agent loop reliable; it makes failures concurrent.

## Recommended skills (small catalog)

Controller owns state/transitions; a skill defines a reusable method; an agent
definition defines role/model/tools/permissions; a hook/policy enforces an invariant;
CI decides whether objective checks passed. Catalog: repo-discovery,
north-star-maintainer, wave-plan, issue-contract, implement-issue, verify-issue,
ci-repair, integrate-wave, wave-review-package, run-retrospective. Each skill:
purpose/trigger, required inputs, preconditions, allowed tools, write scope, procedure,
output schema, validation procedure, stop/escalation, examples, version. Do not build
one giant run-the-project skill. Keep AGENTS.md/CLAUDE.md thin; move task-specific
workflows into on-demand skills. Maintain one canonical skill/policy source, generate
vendor packaging.

## Risk and approval policy

- Low (docs, isolated tests, formatting, generated files): auto-execute + auto-integrate
  after deterministic checks.
- Medium (ordinary app behavior, bounded interfaces): approved wave required;
  independent verification before integration.
- High (auth, authz, dependency upgrades, public API contracts, schema changes, data
  migration): human plan/change approval; security review; controlled integration.
- Critical (production infra, secrets, destructive data ops, billing/identity): human
  approval before execution, merge, and deployment.

Worker agents do not hold production credentials or broad repo-admin rights. Keep code
generation in a sandboxed identity; perform PR publication, merging, and deployment
through separate controlled services. Provider hooks supplement, not replace,
vendor-neutral policy and CI gates. Integrate secure practices into the SDLC (NIST
SSDF), not as a final phase.

## Learning loop (orthogonal)

Run traces + human/Orbit feedback -> classify recurring failures -> create/update
regression eval -> propose smallest skill/instruction/tool/policy change -> run
benchmark + canary (regression loops back) -> reviewed harness-change PR -> runs. Do
not let an agent rewrite its own permanent instructions because one run went poorly.
Classify the failure (missing context, bad instruction adherence, tool failure, model
failure, validation weakness, incorrect task contract) -> replayable eval -> smallest
change -> old-vs-new gate -> PR review -> canary.

## What to measure (outcomes, not activity)

Wave stories accepted without requirement reinterpretation; first-pass verifier success
rate; attempts per accepted task + % stopped for stagnation; tasks added/removed/changed
after wave approval; merge-conflict rate + blocked time from dependency mistakes;
escaped defects + rollback rate per accepted wave; % tasks/stories with complete
evidence packets; human decisions + review minutes per accepted wave; cost + elapsed
time per accepted story by provider/task class; recurring failure rate after the
associated eval/skill change shipped. Do NOT optimize for lines changed, agent turns,
subagents spawned, or issues closed.

## Resulting architecture (target)

Orbit prioritizes outcomes across repositories. Each repository controller snapshots
reality, proposes a bounded wave, and obtains policy/human approval. A deterministic
scheduler converts the approved task DAG into leased, isolated worker runs. Codex or
Claude workers implement tasks and return structured candidates. Fresh-context
verifiers and deterministic checks decide task completion. An integration queue
constructs the cumulative wave, CI and security gates validate it, a preview is
deployed, and human/Orbit review generates the next planning input. Every run is
traced, bounded, and replayable. The controller is the accountable state machine, not
"god of the repo"; models are powerful workers inside explicit contracts; parallelism
is an optimization added after correctness.

